This paper is likely to belong to the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it deals with the optimization of dictionaries for sparse coding using a Hebbian-like learning rule. It also involves the computation of Euclidean projections onto level sets of a sparseness measure, which is a common technique in machine learning. 

It is also likely to belong to the category of cs.CV (Computer Vision) as the paper focuses on image processing tasks and the optimization of dictionaries for image data. 

The paper may also belong to the category of cs.IT (Information Theory) as it involves the computation of projections and sparseness measures, which are concepts commonly used in information theory. 

Additionally, it may belong to the category of cs.NA (Numerical Analysis) as the paper proposes a new algorithm with linear time complexity and constant space complexity for the optimization problem. 

Finally, it may belong to the category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as the paper proposes a new algorithm for dictionary learning that is efficient, expressive, and simple to implement.
